The paper deals with the strategic interaction between agents in a social network, which is a topic that falls under the category of game theory (cs.GT). The use of thresholds to model the adoption of products by agents suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the subfield of social influence (cs.SI). Additionally, the study of social networks and their impact on decision-making aligns with the subfield of computational social science (cs.SOC). The paper also involves analyzing the complexity of determining the existence of Nash equilibria, which is a topic that falls under the category of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). Finally, the use of strategic games and the possibility of not choosing any product suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the subfield of artificial intelligence (cs.AI).
